WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.220 --> 00:00:03.700
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.700 --> 00:00:07.260
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:07.260 --> 00:00:11.110
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:15.960
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:17.020
of videos.

00:00:17.020 --> 00:00:19.029
Thanks for your help.

00:00:19.029 --> 00:00:22.800
In this video we will look at wireless LAN
configuration.

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:27.750
In the past three videos we covered a lot
of theory about wireless networks.

00:00:27.750 --> 00:00:32.239
Finally we’ll get hands-on and see how to
actually build a wireless LAN.

00:00:32.239 --> 00:00:35.900
We will cover exam topics 2.7, 2.8, and 2.9.

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:43.020
2.9 in particular tells us what we need to
be able to configure for the CCNA exam.

00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:49.290
In addition, we will cover exam topic 5.10
which tells us we need to configure WLANs

00:00:49.290 --> 00:00:54.950
using WPA2 PSK, pre-shared key, using the
GUI.

00:00:54.950 --> 00:01:03.150
Note that both topics 2.9 and 5.10 mention
that we must use the GUI, graphical user interface.

00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:07.780
Up to this point in the course we have only
been using the CLI, command line interface,

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:10.010
to configure devices.

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:14.740
You can configure wireless LANs via the CLI
too, but it’s much more common to use the

00:01:14.740 --> 00:01:18.970
GUI, and that’s what Cisco expects you to
know for the exam.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:22.340
Here’s what we’ll cover.

00:01:22.340 --> 00:01:27.860
First I’ll give an introduction to the network
topology I’ll be using for today’s demonstration.

00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:32.420
Then I’ll cover the necessary switch configurations,
since we’ll be connecting all devices to

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:34.710
one central switch.

00:01:34.710 --> 00:01:40.590
Then I’ll show the basic wireless LAN controller
setup, so we will be able to access its GUI

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:44.540
and do the configurations you need to know
for the CCNA.

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:49.020
Then I’ll show how to configure the WLC’s
interfaces, and then we’ll configure some

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:51.260
wireless LANs.

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:54.610
Finally I’ll take a look at some additional
features on the WLC.

00:01:54.610 --> 00:01:59.850
There’s a lot to explore in the WLC and
you only need to know the basics, so I’ll

00:01:59.850 --> 00:02:02.930
just point out a few features you might want
to be aware of.

00:02:02.930 --> 00:02:08.259
As always, watch until the end of the video
for a bonus practice question from Boson software’s

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:13.110
ExSim, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:17.260
For the first time in this course, I will
be using a physical lab.

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:20.150
You can’t make a wireless lab with virtual
devices alone.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:24.550
With that said, a partially virtual lab is
possible.

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:29.920
I could have, for example, used a virtual
WLC instead of a physical one, but I was able

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:35.610
to get this hardware second hand for a cheap
price, so I decided to use all physical devices.

00:02:35.610 --> 00:02:40.910
Fortunately, you don’t have to purchase
physical hardware to practice wireless configuration

00:02:40.910 --> 00:02:42.700
for the CCNA.

00:02:42.700 --> 00:02:47.160
Packet Tracer does offer some basic WLC and
AP functionality.

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:52.160
It’s limited, but it’s good enough to
practice what you need for the CCNA.

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:57.590
Anyway, in this topology I have one switch,
one wireless LAN controller, and two wireless

00:02:57.590 --> 00:02:59.410
APs.

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:03.650
By the way, I haven’t connected any power
cables to the APs, but they are still receiving

00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:05.180
power.

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:09.410
Can you guess how they are receiving power
without a dedicated power cable?

00:03:09.410 --> 00:03:13.050
The answer is PoE of course, power over ethernet.

00:03:13.050 --> 00:03:19.480
A single ethernet cable is used to both pass
data and provide power to the device.

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:24.110
You can see here on the switch that its interfaces
are PoE capable.

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:29.959
Actually, the WLC itself also has two PoE
capable ports, although I’m not using them

00:03:29.959 --> 00:03:30.959
in this lab.

00:03:30.959 --> 00:03:38.120
So, an AP could be directly connected to the
WLC itself and receive power via PoE.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:41.780
Here’s the network topology.

00:03:41.780 --> 00:03:47.310
Note that the WLC connects to the switch via
a LAG, link aggregation group.

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:53.660
You might remember from my EtherChannel video
that LAG is just another term for EtherChannel.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:58.970
But in the context of wireless LAN controllers,
we always use the term LAG.

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:04.890
And also note that WLCs only support static
LAG, no PAgP or LACP.

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:10.380
So, when we configure the switch’s interfaces
to form the LAG we will use the command CHANNEL-GROUP

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:15.610
1 MODE ON, not MODE ACTIVE or MORE DESIRABLE.

00:04:15.610 --> 00:04:19.760
You don’t have to connect the WLC to the
switch using a LAG, but it’s a good idea

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.820
to provide additional throughput and redundancy.

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:27.500
I will use three VLANs, three subnets, in
this network.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:32.790
VLAN10 is the management VLAN, its subnet
will be 192.168.1.0/24.

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:41.060
VLAN 100 will be called ‘Internal’, its
subnet will be 10.0.0.0/24.

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:43.560
And VLAN 200 will be called ‘Guest’.

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:45.160
Its subnet will be 10.1.0.0/24.

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:53.390
Note that only VLAN 100 and VLAN 200 will
be mapped to a wireless LAN and advertised

00:04:53.390 --> 00:04:54.600
by the APs.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:05:00.389
VLAN 10 will just be used for connecting to
the network devices, the WLC, switch, and

00:05:00.389 --> 00:05:07.610
APs, and managing them for example via their
CLI with an SSH connection.

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:12.860
VLAN100 will be mapped to an SSID, Internal,
which the APs will advertise and clients can

00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:14.590
connect to.

00:05:14.590 --> 00:05:16.500
Same for VLAN200.

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:21.750
It will be mapped to an SSID called Guest
and advertised by the APs.

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:24.780
Devices will be able to associate with that
SSID too.

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:29.820
Now, in this video I won’t be doing any
advanced policies to control traffic, but

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:35.699
in a real deployment you could limit the Guest
SSID to Internet access only, whereas clients

00:05:35.699 --> 00:05:42.290
associated with the Internal SSID could access
all internal company resources, for example.

00:05:42.290 --> 00:05:47.880
The switch will have an SVI in each VLAN,
the .1 address of each subnet.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:53.740
And the WLC will have an IP address in each
VLAN too, the .100 of each subnet.

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:59.230
The APs will need an IP address in the management
VLAN so they can communicate with the WLC,

00:05:59.230 --> 00:06:01.669
but they will get their IP addresses via DHCP.

00:06:01.669 --> 00:06:03.540
So, where’s the DHCP server?

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:11.509
The WLC could be the server, but I’ll configure
the switch as both a DHCP server and an NTP

00:06:11.509 --> 00:06:13.490
server for this network.

00:06:13.490 --> 00:06:20.509
I want to remind you that, since we’re using
a WLC, a split-MAC deployment, the switch’s

00:06:20.509 --> 00:06:24.039
interfaces connecting to the APs are access
ports.

00:06:24.039 --> 00:06:29.150
Only the WLC needs to connect via a trunk
port with all of the necessary VLANs.

00:06:29.150 --> 00:06:32.470
However the APs will form CAPWAP tunnels to
the WLC.

00:06:32.470 --> 00:06:38.050
So, let’s say this client associated with
the Internal WLAN wants to communicate with

00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:41.550
its default gateway, which is SW1’s VLAN
100 SVI.

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:47.120
The traffic passes through the CAPWAP tunnel
to the WLC.

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:52.949
On the WLC, the Internal WLAN is mapped to
VLAN100, so it will forward the traffic in

00:06:52.949 --> 00:06:55.040
VLAN100 to SW1.

00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:59.509
SW1 then sends it back via the same path.

00:06:59.509 --> 00:07:04.449
What if the client associated with the Internal
WLAN wants to send traffic to the client associated

00:07:04.449 --> 00:07:07.000
with the Guest WLAN?

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:12.360
It will send the traffic to its default gateway,
SW1, following the same path as before.

00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:18.230
SW1 routes it to VLAN 200 and sends it to
the WLC, which will send it to the destination

00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:20.800
client via the CAPWAP tunnel and the AP.

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:26.550
So, that’s just a quick review of how traffic
travels in a split-MAC deployment like this.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:32.030
So, let’s finally start our configurations,
first SW1.

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:35.690
All of these configurations will be review
for you, so let’s just quickly take a look

00:07:35.690 --> 00:07:36.780
at them.

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:40.610
Here’s the first half of the configurations.

00:07:40.610 --> 00:07:47.240
First I created the three VLANs, 10, 100,
and 200, and gave them appropriate names.

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:53.080
Then I configured fastethernet 0/6, 7, and
8 as access ports in VLAN10.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:59.310
F0/7 and 8 connect to the APs, so why do you
think I configured F0/6 too?

00:07:59.310 --> 00:08:07.650
It’s because I will later connect my PC
to F0/6 to gain access to WLC1’s GUI.

00:08:07.650 --> 00:08:12.449
A device’s CLI, command line interface,
can be accessed via the console port, or connected

00:08:12.449 --> 00:08:15.450
to over the network using Telnet or SSH.

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:21.870
However, the GUI, graphical user interface,
cannot be accessed via the console port.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:26.039
You must connect over the network, using HTTP
or HTTPS.

00:08:26.039 --> 00:08:30.450
I’ll show you how to do that when I move
on to configure the WLC.

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:38.529
Anyway, I then configured SW1’s F0/1 and
F0/2 as a static LAG, static etherchannel.

00:08:38.529 --> 00:08:43.519
Remember that WLCs only support static LAG,
no PAgP or LACP.

00:08:43.519 --> 00:08:51.040
So, you must use the command CHANNEL-GROUP
1 MODE ON, not MODE DESIRABLE or MODE ACTIVE.

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:55.149
And finally I configured the port-channel
interface as a trunk and allowed VLANs 10,

00:08:55.149 --> 00:08:58.709
100, and 200.

00:08:58.709 --> 00:09:01.529
And here’s the second half of the configurations.

00:09:01.529 --> 00:09:04.439
I configured an SVI for each VLAN.

00:09:04.439 --> 00:09:07.350
These will be used as the default gateway
for their subnets.

00:09:07.350 --> 00:09:13.110
I then configured a DHCP pool for each VLAN,
and notice that I used the DEFAULT-ROUTER

00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:20.129
command and specified SW1’s SVI IP addresses
as the default gateway for each subnet.

00:09:20.129 --> 00:09:25.290
The VLAN10 DHCP pool will be used by the APs
to get their IP addresses, which they need

00:09:25.290 --> 00:09:28.449
to communicate with the WLC.

00:09:28.449 --> 00:09:36.639
Note that the VLAN10 pool has an additional
command, OPTION 43 IP 192.168.1.100.

00:09:36.639 --> 00:09:43.190
DHCP option 43 can be used to tell the APs
the IP address of their WLC.

00:09:43.190 --> 00:09:49.911
So, when the APs get an IP address from SW1,
it will tell them ‘your WLC is at IP address

00:09:49.911 --> 00:09:56.709
192.168.1.100’, and the APs will then try
to communicate with the WLC and form their

00:09:56.709 --> 00:09:59.040
CAPWAP tunnels.

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:01.800
Although in this case it’s actually not
necessary.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:07.689
The APs and WLC are in the same subnet, the
same local VLAN, and APs will send broadcast

00:10:07.689 --> 00:10:13.709
CAPWAP discovery messages to check if there
are any WLCs in the local subnet.

00:10:13.709 --> 00:10:20.829
The WLC will hear those broadcast messages,
so the APs will be able to join the WLC.

00:10:20.829 --> 00:10:26.319
But just be aware that DHCP option 43 might
be necessary if the WLC is located somewhere

00:10:26.319 --> 00:10:31.459
that it won’t be able to hear the broadcast
discovery messages from the APs.

00:10:31.459 --> 00:10:34.910
Remember that one for the exam, DHCP option
43.

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:38.319
So, that’s the VLAN 10 pool.

00:10:38.319 --> 00:10:42.309
The VLAN 100 and VLAN 200 pools will be used
by wireless clients.

00:10:42.309 --> 00:10:45.910
SW1 will assign IP addresses to them using
DHCP.

00:10:45.910 --> 00:10:49.980
Okay, the final command I used on the switch
is NTP MASTER.

00:10:49.980 --> 00:10:57.990
This will make it an NTP server, and I’ll
later tell the WLC to use SW1 as its NTP server.

00:10:57.990 --> 00:11:03.269
Okay, that’s all of the configuration needed
on SW1.

00:11:03.269 --> 00:11:05.139
Now let’s finally configure the WLC.

00:11:05.139 --> 00:11:08.920
I can’t connect to its GUI yet.

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:13.059
First I need to connect to its console port
and do some basic setup in the CLI.

00:11:13.059 --> 00:11:16.759
So, let’s take a look at that.

00:11:16.759 --> 00:11:21.079
When the WLC first boots up you will be greeted
with a configuration wizard.

00:11:21.079 --> 00:11:25.689
So, you don’t actually need to know any
CLI commands for the WLC to do this basic

00:11:25.689 --> 00:11:28.670
setup, the wizard will walk you through it.

00:11:28.670 --> 00:11:33.550
First, it asks me if I would like to terminate
autoinstall.

00:11:33.550 --> 00:11:39.329
Autoinstall can be used to automatically download
the WLC’s configuration from a TFTP server.

00:11:39.329 --> 00:11:43.019
I won’t do that, so I press enter to skip
it.

00:11:43.019 --> 00:11:47.519
Note that the value in the square brackets,
yes in this case, is the default.

00:11:47.519 --> 00:11:52.740
You don’t have to type yes, if you just
hit enter it will assume ‘yes’.

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:58.369
Then I entered the system name, the host name,
of WLC1, as well as a username and password

00:11:58.369 --> 00:12:01.139
that I will use later to log in to the device.

00:12:01.139 --> 00:12:05.610
It then asks me if I want to enable link aggregation,
LAG.

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:10.319
Notice that there are two options in square
brackets, yes and NO.

00:12:10.319 --> 00:12:14.619
However, NO is in upper case letters, so it
is the default.

00:12:14.619 --> 00:12:20.279
If I just hit enter, the device will assume
I mean NO, I don’t want to enable LAG.

00:12:20.279 --> 00:12:25.999
However in this case I will be using a LAG
to connect to the switch, so I selected yes.

00:12:25.999 --> 00:12:29.499
Then I enter some values for the management
interface.

00:12:29.499 --> 00:12:32.329
Note that this isn’t a physical interface,
a physical port.

00:12:32.329 --> 00:12:36.100
It is a virtual interface in the WLC.

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:44.929
I gave it an IP of 192.168.1.100, a /24 netmask,
specified SW1’s IP address of .1 as the

00:12:44.929 --> 00:12:51.069
default gateway, gave it a VLAN ID of 10,
and again specified SW1’s IP address of

00:12:51.069 --> 00:12:55.019
.1 as the DHCP server.

00:12:55.019 --> 00:12:58.809
Let’s continue with the WLC’s basic setup.

00:12:58.809 --> 00:13:02.899
This is still part of the configuration wizard,
so I’m answering questions instead of actually

00:13:02.899 --> 00:13:05.769
inputting commands in the CLI.

00:13:05.769 --> 00:13:09.920
These three options at the top are a bit beyond
what you need to know for the CCNA, but let

00:13:09.920 --> 00:13:12.019
me briefly explain them.

00:13:12.019 --> 00:13:16.910
The virtual gateway IP is an IP address used
when the WLC is communicating directly with

00:13:16.910 --> 00:13:21.559
wireless clients such as when relaying DHCP
requests.

00:13:21.559 --> 00:13:26.040
The multicast IP address is used when forwarding
traffic to its APs.

00:13:26.040 --> 00:13:30.790
Note that I selected an IP address in the
class D range, which is reserved for multicast

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:32.060
addresses.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:37.359
And the mobility/RF group name is used when
you have multiple WLCs and you want them to

00:13:37.359 --> 00:13:39.109
work together.

00:13:39.109 --> 00:13:43.290
I doubt you’ll be asked about these on the
CCNA exam.

00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:47.669
Next in the setup it asks us to configure
a wireless LAN, starting with the SSID.

00:13:47.669 --> 00:13:53.139
I’ll show you how to do this in the GUI
soon, but first it requires us to make one

00:13:53.139 --> 00:13:55.059
in this configuration wizard.

00:13:55.059 --> 00:14:00.279
I use the SSID internal, and then I accept
the default settings for the next question

00:14:00.279 --> 00:14:04.279
about DHCP bridging mode, leaving it disabled.

00:14:04.279 --> 00:14:10.019
For wireless clients’ DHCP requests to reach
the DHCP server, SW1, they must pass through

00:14:10.019 --> 00:14:11.560
WLC1 first.

00:14:11.560 --> 00:14:18.139
If DHCP bridging mode is enabled, the WLC
becomes totally transparent to the clients.

00:14:18.139 --> 00:14:22.060
It will appear as if they are communicating
directly to the server.

00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:24.929
But that’s not necessary here, so I’ll
leave it disabled.

00:14:24.929 --> 00:14:30.309
I also accept the default for the next setting,
allow static IP addresses.

00:14:30.309 --> 00:14:33.569
This means that clients are allowed to use
static IP addresses if they prefer.

00:14:33.569 --> 00:14:36.109
They don’t have to use DHCP.

00:14:36.109 --> 00:14:41.579
And finally I choose not to configure a RADIUS
server now, and it gives me a warning.

00:14:41.579 --> 00:14:46.389
The default WLAN security policy requires
a RADIUS server.

00:14:46.389 --> 00:14:50.859
We will change the WLAN security policy to
use a pre-shared key, so we don’t need to

00:14:50.859 --> 00:14:53.720
configure a RADIUS server.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:58.699
Next I have to enter a country code, or a
list of country codes, and I entered FR for

00:14:58.699 --> 00:15:00.009
France.

00:15:00.009 --> 00:15:02.100
Why did I select France?

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:07.249
This is actually very important and was a
problem for me when getting this lab set up.

00:15:07.249 --> 00:15:11.759
Because I live in Japan, I originally entered
JP here, but then my APs weren’t able to

00:15:11.759 --> 00:15:14.779
join with the WLC.

00:15:14.779 --> 00:15:16.549
Here is the reason for that.

00:15:16.549 --> 00:15:19.489
Look at the model name of this AP here.

00:15:19.489 --> 00:15:22.480
Specifically, this E in the model name.

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:27.899
This E indicates the regulatory domain of
the device, E meaning Europe.

00:15:27.899 --> 00:15:33.199
If the regulatory domain of the country specified
in the WLC configuration doesn’t match the

00:15:33.199 --> 00:15:39.109
regulatory domain of the AP, the AP won’t
be able to join the WLC.

00:15:39.109 --> 00:15:42.309
You can check the regulatory domain of each
country here.

00:15:42.309 --> 00:15:49.309
In Canada or the US, for example, -A is used
instead of -E. So, because my APs are -E,

00:15:49.309 --> 00:15:52.850
I configured a country in Europe on my WLC.

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:56.959
I doubt that you have to know this for the
CCNA exam, but if you have your own wireless

00:15:56.959 --> 00:16:01.929
lab with second-hand devices, you should be
aware of this or you might run into problems.

00:16:01.929 --> 00:16:06.470
Okay, here’s the final section of the initial
WLC setup.

00:16:06.470 --> 00:16:14.889
I choose to enable 802.11b, a, and g, as well
as auto-RF which allows the WLC to automatically

00:16:14.889 --> 00:16:19.389
select which channels to use and how much
transmit power to use.

00:16:19.389 --> 00:16:21.809
This is much better than doing everything
manually.

00:16:21.809 --> 00:16:27.459
I then configure some NTP settings so my WLC
has the correct time.

00:16:27.459 --> 00:16:30.149
Finally I save the settings, and the device
resets.

00:16:30.149 --> 00:16:33.970
That’s all for the WLC initial setup.

00:16:33.970 --> 00:16:40.060
So, now that the WLC’s initial setup is
complete it has an IP address in the management

00:16:40.060 --> 00:16:42.309
VLAN, VLAN 10.

00:16:42.309 --> 00:16:47.970
So, instead of connecting my PC to the WLC’s
console port and using the CLI, I will connect

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:49.569
my PC to the switch.

00:16:49.569 --> 00:16:55.540
Remember, I configured SW1’s F0/6 interface
in VLAN10, the management VLAN.

00:16:55.540 --> 00:17:02.470
Now I will be able to use HTTP or HTTPS to
access the WLC’s GUI in a web browser.

00:17:02.470 --> 00:17:09.890
So, I enter WLC1’s IP address, 192.168.1.100,
in a web browser.

00:17:09.890 --> 00:17:13.370
However I get a warning that my connection
is not private.

00:17:13.370 --> 00:17:16.760
The error is certificate authority invalid.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:20.250
This just means my PC doesn’t trust the
certificate on my WLC.

00:17:20.250 --> 00:17:22.870
But that’s not an issue.

00:17:22.870 --> 00:17:25.860
Next I clicked on advanced here.

00:17:25.860 --> 00:17:30.740
And now I get the option to proceed to 192.168.1.100.

00:17:30.740 --> 00:17:35.230
If your browser gives you a warning like this
when visiting a website you should be careful,

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:39.790
but I know that I’m just connecting to WLC1
on my local network, so there’s no issue

00:17:39.790 --> 00:17:41.750
here.

00:17:41.750 --> 00:17:44.659
And here is the login screen for the Cisco
WLC.

00:17:44.659 --> 00:17:48.889
So, I click on the login button.

00:17:48.889 --> 00:17:53.690
And then I enter the admin username and password
I created in the initial setup earlier.

00:17:53.690 --> 00:17:58.360
And here is the dashboard for the WLC.

00:17:58.360 --> 00:18:00.639
Let me point out a few things.

00:18:00.639 --> 00:18:04.950
Notice that it shows which interfaces are
up, the green ones, and which are down, the

00:18:04.950 --> 00:18:06.690
red ones.

00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:11.690
Those two green interfaces are forming a LAG
and are connected to the switch.

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:16.059
Here there is a summary of some information
about the controller, such as its management

00:18:16.059 --> 00:18:22.700
IP, system name, up time, temperature, CPU
and memory usage, etc.

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:26.730
And here is a summary of the access points
that have joined the WLC.

00:18:26.730 --> 00:18:29.080
Note that both of my APs have already joined.

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:33.039
Okay, now let’s actually do some configurations
on the WLC.

00:18:33.039 --> 00:18:39.159
First, I’ll go to the CONTROLLER tab up
top here.

00:18:39.159 --> 00:18:46.640
From the controller tab, I clicked on interfaces,
and here you can see the WLC’s interfaces.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:53.250
Note that these are not physical ports, but
logical or virtual interfaces in the WLC.

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:57.710
In most contexts we can use the terms port
and interface interchangeably.

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:04.670
However, in the context of WLCs, port means
physical port and interface means logical

00:19:04.670 --> 00:19:08.450
interface within the device

00:19:08.450 --> 00:19:13.250
Before configuring the interfaces, let me
briefly explain the ports and interfaces of

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:14.809
a WLC.

00:19:14.809 --> 00:19:20.179
Again, WLC ports are the physical interfaces
that cables connect to.

00:19:20.179 --> 00:19:27.010
And interfaces are the logical interfaces
within the WLC, like SVIs on a switch.

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:32.000
WLCs have a few different kinds of ports,
let me introduce them.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.010
The service port is a dedicated management
port, it is used for out-of-band management.

00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:42.660
That means keeping management traffic totally
separate from regular data traffic, not using

00:19:42.660 --> 00:19:44.580
the same physical interface.

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:50.200
My WLC doesn’t have a dedicated service
port, so the management traffic will use the

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:54.260
same physical ports as the regular data traffic.

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:58.549
Note that the service port must connect to
a switch access port because it only supports

00:19:58.549 --> 00:20:00.850
one VLAN.

00:20:00.850 --> 00:20:05.460
Also this port can be used to connect to the
device while it is booting up, perform system

00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:10.490
recovery, and other system management tasks
like that.

00:20:10.490 --> 00:20:13.139
Next are distribution system ports.

00:20:13.139 --> 00:20:17.509
These are the standard network interfaces
that connect to the distribution system, remember

00:20:17.509 --> 00:20:21.570
that’s the 802.11 term for the wired network.

00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:25.950
And these are the interfaces that are used
for regular data traffic to and from the wireless

00:20:25.950 --> 00:20:27.510
clients.

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:31.980
Note that these ports usually connect to switch
trunk ports, and if multiple distribution

00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:36.740
ports are used they can form a LAG, as I did
in my network.

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:42.789
Then there is the console port, which can
be either RJ45 or USB, or perhaps the WLC

00:20:42.789 --> 00:20:44.639
has both.

00:20:44.639 --> 00:20:49.550
And there might also be a redundancy port,
which can be used to connect to another WLC

00:20:49.550 --> 00:20:53.179
to form a high availability, HA, pair.

00:20:53.179 --> 00:20:58.640
This means you have redundant WLCs, so if
one fails the other one can continue to support

00:20:58.640 --> 00:20:59.850
the network.

00:20:59.850 --> 00:21:07.409
My WLC is a bit old, so it just has an RJ45
console port and four distribution system

00:21:07.409 --> 00:21:09.000
ports.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:14.030
These aren’t ports but it has a reset button
and some status LEDs on the front as well.

00:21:14.030 --> 00:21:20.299
To show you the other kinds of ports, let’s
look at a more modern WLC from Cisco.

00:21:20.299 --> 00:21:27.429
So, here is a pair of WLCs, let’s go through
each of these numbers, from 1 to 9.

00:21:27.429 --> 00:21:29.220
Number 1 is the service port.

00:21:29.220 --> 00:21:34.080
Again, this can be used for out-of-band management,
to keep the management traffic physically

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:37.049
separate from the data traffic.

00:21:37.049 --> 00:21:43.409
Number 2 is an RJ45 console port, and number
3 is a USB console port.

00:21:43.409 --> 00:21:45.659
Then there is another USB port.

00:21:45.659 --> 00:21:50.250
This isn’t a network port, it’s just a
regular USB port used to transfer files to

00:21:50.250 --> 00:21:54.759
the WLC, for example a new OS version to update
the software.

00:21:54.759 --> 00:22:00.630
Next, number five is a distribution system
port, and it supports multi-gigabit speeds,

00:22:00.630 --> 00:22:02.470
beyond 1-gig.

00:22:02.470 --> 00:22:08.480
And then four more distribution system ports,
these ones are regular 1-gig ports.

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:13.789
Number 7 isn’t a port, it’s a reset button
like on my WLC, and there are status LEDs

00:22:13.789 --> 00:22:18.870
too indicating the status of the device, those
are number 8 on this image.

00:22:18.870 --> 00:22:21.929
And finally number 9 is the redundancy port.

00:22:21.929 --> 00:22:26.660
You could connect these two WLCs by their
redundancy ports and they would form a redundant

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:28.169
pair.

00:22:28.169 --> 00:22:32.950
Okay, those are the different kinds of physical
WLC ports.

00:22:32.950 --> 00:22:36.690
WLCs have a few different kinds of interfaces,
too.

00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:41.659
The management interface is used for so-called
management traffic, meaning communications

00:22:41.659 --> 00:22:49.139
used to manage devices such as Telnet or SSH
connections to the CLI, HTTP or HTTPS connections

00:22:49.139 --> 00:22:55.919
to the GUI, RADIUS authentication traffic,
NTP and Syslog traffic, etc.

00:22:55.919 --> 00:23:01.379
Remember that, to connect to the GUI of the
WLC, I accessed the management IP address

00:23:01.379 --> 00:23:05.149
of 192.168.1.100.

00:23:05.149 --> 00:23:12.070
CAPWAP tunnels between the APs and WLC are
also formed to and from this interface.

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:14.929
Next there also might be a redundancy management
interface.

00:23:14.929 --> 00:23:21.179
When two WLCs are connected by their redundancy
ports, one WLC becomes active and the other

00:23:21.179 --> 00:23:23.149
becomes standby.

00:23:23.149 --> 00:23:28.029
To manage the active WLC you can connect to
the management interface, but to manage the

00:23:28.029 --> 00:23:32.559
standby WLC you can use the redundancy management
interface.

00:23:32.559 --> 00:23:35.900
Next there is the virtual interface.

00:23:35.900 --> 00:23:39.980
Remember I had to configure this IP address
when initially setting up the WLC?

00:23:39.980 --> 00:23:45.549
It’s used when communicating with wireless
clients to relay DHCP requests, perform client

00:23:45.549 --> 00:23:49.529
web authentication if necessary, etc.

00:23:49.529 --> 00:23:52.100
Next there is a service port interface.

00:23:52.100 --> 00:23:56.980
If the WLC’s service port is used, this
interface is bound to it and used for out-of-band

00:23:56.980 --> 00:24:01.019
management instead of the regular management
interface.

00:24:01.019 --> 00:24:06.279
And finally there are dynamic interfaces,
these are used to map a wireless LAN to a

00:24:06.279 --> 00:24:07.279
VLAN.

00:24:07.279 --> 00:24:11.860
For example, traffic from the internal wireless
LAN will be sent to the wired network from

00:24:11.860 --> 00:24:14.269
the WLC’s Internal dynamic interface.

00:24:14.269 --> 00:24:19.889
So, let’s go back to the GUI and configure
a couple dynamic interfaces to be used for

00:24:19.889 --> 00:24:22.179
our wireless LANs.

00:24:22.179 --> 00:24:25.760
Here’s the interfaces menu again.

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:30.900
I’ll click New to create a new interface.

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:35.879
First I’ll make the interface for the Internal
WLAN, and notice I’m mapping it to VLAN

00:24:35.879 --> 00:24:36.970
100.

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:40.230
Then I’ll click on Apply.

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:43.799
I am then brought to this screen where I can
enter more details.

00:24:43.799 --> 00:24:49.830
The VLAN ID was already set to 100 from the
previous screen, but I entered the IP address,

00:24:49.830 --> 00:24:53.159
netmask, gateway, and DHCP server address.

00:24:53.159 --> 00:24:57.730
That’s all I need to enter here, so I clicked
on Apply.

00:24:57.730 --> 00:25:01.600
By the way, feel free to pause the video at
any point if you want to take a look at the

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:04.899
different settings available in any of these
menus.

00:25:04.899 --> 00:25:09.919
So, now the dynamic interface called ‘internal’
has been created.

00:25:09.919 --> 00:25:15.200
I will map this interface to the Internal
WLAN later, but now I have to create one more

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:16.320
interface.

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:20.490
That is the guest interface, so I click on
New again.

00:25:20.490 --> 00:25:26.130
and then at this screen I specify a name of
Guest and I map it to VLAN 200, since that

00:25:26.130 --> 00:25:29.710
will be used for the guest WLAN and VLAN.

00:25:29.710 --> 00:25:32.539
Then I click apply.

00:25:32.539 --> 00:25:38.309
Again at this screen I enter the IP information
needed for the Guest interface, the IP address,

00:25:38.309 --> 00:25:43.769
netmask, gateway, and DHCP server address,
and then click apply to finish creating this

00:25:43.769 --> 00:25:45.240
interface.

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:50.300
Okay, now the WLC has all of the interfaces
it needs.

00:25:50.300 --> 00:25:53.669
Finally let’s go to configuring some WLANs.

00:25:53.669 --> 00:25:58.980
To do that, just click on the WLAN tab here
at the top of the GUI.

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:02.720
So, here’s the WLANs tab.

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:06.490
Note that one WLAN, Internal, already exists.

00:26:06.490 --> 00:26:10.019
That is because I made it during the initial
setup in the CLI.

00:26:10.019 --> 00:26:13.850
However, I still have to make some changes
to this one.

00:26:13.850 --> 00:26:17.730
For example, look at the security policies
column on the right.

00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:23.309
It is configured to use 802.1X authentication,
so WPA enterprise mode.

00:26:23.309 --> 00:26:29.570
But for the CCNA we have to configure Pre-shared
key authentication, in others words WPA personal

00:26:29.570 --> 00:26:30.570
mode.

00:26:30.570 --> 00:26:38.830
So, if I click on the WLAN ID, the number
1 on the left, I am able to edit this WLAN.

00:26:38.830 --> 00:26:45.850
The profile name is Internal, it’s a WLAN,
the SSID is internal, and it’s enabled.

00:26:45.850 --> 00:26:47.110
That all looks good.

00:26:47.110 --> 00:26:49.769
Here’s the security policy.

00:26:49.769 --> 00:26:54.580
As I said before I’ll have to change that,
but it’s done on the security tab, not here.

00:26:54.580 --> 00:26:57.350
Now, here’s a problem.

00:26:57.350 --> 00:27:01.179
Currently the Internal WLAN is mapped to the
management interface.

00:27:01.179 --> 00:27:05.929
That’s not correct, we should map it to
the Internal dynamic interface.

00:27:05.929 --> 00:27:08.309
So, that’s what I did.

00:27:08.309 --> 00:27:11.730
I selected the Internal interface here.

00:27:11.730 --> 00:27:17.309
Now it’s time to go to the security tab
and change that security policy to use a PSK

00:27:17.309 --> 00:27:19.490
instead of 802.1X.

00:27:19.490 --> 00:27:23.570
Here’s the security tab.

00:27:23.570 --> 00:27:27.590
First up, notice what’s called the ‘layer
2 security’ setting.

00:27:27.590 --> 00:27:34.289
This is where we can select things like WEP,
802.1X, different versions of WPA, etc.

00:27:34.289 --> 00:27:41.340
Currently it’s WPA+WPA2, which is what we
should select for the CCNA.

00:27:41.340 --> 00:27:46.720
For your reference, here are the layer 2 security
options available on my WLC.

00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:48.960
Note that the newer WPA3 isn’t supported.

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:54.380
But that’s fine, we’re supposed to use
WPA2 for the CCNA.

00:27:54.380 --> 00:27:58.450
Next, look down here at authentication key
management.

00:27:58.450 --> 00:28:01.140
802.1X is selected.

00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:04.619
This is what we want to change, it should
be PSK.

00:28:04.619 --> 00:28:14.379
So, I scrolled down a bit, de-selected 802.1X,
and selected PSK, pre-shared key, instead.

00:28:14.379 --> 00:28:18.331
Notice that the PSK can then be specified
either in ASCII or in HEX.

00:28:18.331 --> 00:28:25.710
HEX means hexadecimal, the same number system
we learned for MAC addresses and IPv6 addresses.

00:28:25.710 --> 00:28:30.539
ASCII means American Standard Code for Information
Interchange.

00:28:30.539 --> 00:28:36.309
Basically, it means you can enter your password
using regular letters, numbers, and symbols.

00:28:36.309 --> 00:28:43.340
So, I selected ASCII, entered a short password,
clicked on apply, and then I got an error

00:28:43.340 --> 00:28:49.529
message, stating that the PSK in ASCII format
should be at least 8 characters in length.

00:28:49.529 --> 00:28:54.259
This is to make sure the password is secure,
not easy to crack.

00:28:54.259 --> 00:28:59.679
So this time I entered a longer password,
clicked on apply, and it worked.

00:28:59.679 --> 00:29:05.869
We won’t configure any ‘Layer 3’ security
methods, but for your reference I checked

00:29:05.869 --> 00:29:13.400
the Layer 3 tab and you can see that my WLC
supports something called Web Policy.

00:29:13.400 --> 00:29:20.309
If I select web policy, various options appear,
such as web authentication and passthrough.

00:29:20.309 --> 00:29:25.019
Web authentication means that, after wireless
clients get an IP address and try to access

00:29:25.019 --> 00:29:30.660
a web page, they will have to enter a username
and password to authenticate.

00:29:30.660 --> 00:29:35.440
Web passthrough is similar, but no username
or password are required.

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:40.259
Instead a warning or statement is displayed
and the client just has to agree to gain access

00:29:40.259 --> 00:29:42.149
to the Internet.

00:29:42.149 --> 00:29:46.889
In either of these examples, the Layer 2 authentication
can just be open.

00:29:46.889 --> 00:29:51.710
This is common for public WiFi for example
at a cafe.

00:29:51.710 --> 00:29:57.049
Note that the conditional and splash page
web redirect options are similar, but additionally

00:29:57.049 --> 00:30:00.869
require 802.1X layer 2 authentication.

00:30:00.869 --> 00:30:05.659
Anyway, as I said before we won’t configure
any of these, so let’s move on without enabling

00:30:05.659 --> 00:30:08.669
web policy.

00:30:08.669 --> 00:30:14.389
There is also a AAA servers tab, but since
we are using PSK authentication only there’s

00:30:14.389 --> 00:30:17.220
no need to set up anything like a RADIUS server.

00:30:17.220 --> 00:30:21.379
So, let’s go to the QoS tab now.

00:30:21.379 --> 00:30:24.649
Here’s the QoS tab.

00:30:24.649 --> 00:30:28.999
The only thing you need to be aware of here
is the QoS setting, which is Silver, best

00:30:28.999 --> 00:30:32.350
effort, by default.

00:30:32.350 --> 00:30:34.460
Here are the options available.

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:39.779
This is how you can control what quality of
service is provided to the wireless clients.

00:30:39.779 --> 00:30:44.460
Platinum should be used for voice, for example
WiFi IP phones.

00:30:44.460 --> 00:30:47.149
Gold should be used for video traffic.

00:30:47.149 --> 00:30:52.179
Silver is the default, and bronze is given
the lowest priority, for what’s called ‘background’

00:30:52.179 --> 00:30:53.179
traffic.

00:30:53.179 --> 00:30:57.700
Anyway, in this case I’ll just leave it
at silver, but for the exam definitely know

00:30:57.700 --> 00:31:02.600
these four QoS settings, platinum, gold, silver,
and bronze.

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:08.110
Okay, finally we’ll take a look at the advanced
tab.

00:31:08.110 --> 00:31:10.620
In this tab there are lots of different settings.

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:15.370
For example, you could configure a maximum
number of clients allowed.

00:31:15.370 --> 00:31:17.630
Currently it is 0, meaning there is no maximum.

00:31:17.630 --> 00:31:22.249
Okay, I’ll scroll down to see other settings.

00:31:22.249 --> 00:31:26.570
Here are some additional settings, for example
if you want to enable FlexConnect you can

00:31:26.570 --> 00:31:28.309
do it here.

00:31:28.309 --> 00:31:32.710
But I won’t touch these advanced settings,
so I will just click on Apply to finish editing

00:31:32.710 --> 00:31:34.809
this WLAN.

00:31:34.809 --> 00:31:39.440
Okay, the Internal WLAN is done.

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:44.909
Next I’ll click on Go here to create a new
WLAN, the guest WLAN.

00:31:44.909 --> 00:31:51.000
Okay, since we’re creating a new WLAN this
time we have to specify the profile name,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:54.230
SSID, and ID first.

00:31:54.230 --> 00:31:59.499
The profile name is used to identify this
WLAN in the WLC, and usually you’ll just

00:31:59.499 --> 00:32:03.580
make it the same as the SSID, as I did in
this case.

00:32:03.580 --> 00:32:07.919
Note that the profile name and SSID don’t
have to be the same, though.

00:32:07.919 --> 00:32:12.870
Then there is the ID, a unique number that
identifies the WLAN.

00:32:12.870 --> 00:32:16.710
The Internal WLAN was 1, so I’ll make this
one 2.

00:32:16.710 --> 00:32:20.100
So, I’ll click on apply to move forward.

00:32:20.100 --> 00:32:24.090
Okay, now we’re at that same page.

00:32:24.090 --> 00:32:28.570
Since we already went through all of the settings
for the Internal WLAN, I’ll go through this

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:29.570
quickly.

00:32:29.570 --> 00:32:32.690
There are two things we should change on this
general tab.

00:32:32.690 --> 00:32:34.909
First, the status.

00:32:34.909 --> 00:32:39.940
The Internal WLAN was already enabled, but
this new one is not, so we should enable it

00:32:39.940 --> 00:32:41.029
here.

00:32:41.029 --> 00:32:45.629
And secondly, we should change the interface
to the Guest interface we created earlier.

00:32:45.629 --> 00:32:48.809
Okay, I changed the settings.

00:32:48.809 --> 00:32:53.749
Now, the only other change we have to make
is to change the security policy to use a

00:32:53.749 --> 00:32:55.759
PSK on the security tab.

00:32:55.759 --> 00:33:01.100
I’ve already shown you how to do that, so
for the sake of time let’s skip over that.

00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:06.779
Okay, now we have two WLANs, the internal
WLAN and the guest WLAN.

00:33:06.779 --> 00:33:12.149
So, let’s return to the monitoring dashboard
and see if anything is different.

00:33:12.149 --> 00:33:14.960
Here’s the dashboard again.

00:33:14.960 --> 00:33:19.940
I scrolled down a bit, and you can see that
we have 0 clients associated with the APs.

00:33:19.940 --> 00:33:23.100
So, let’s change that.

00:33:23.100 --> 00:33:27.980
On my iPhone you can see that the guest and
internal WLANs are visible, so I’ll join

00:33:27.980 --> 00:33:30.429
with a few of my devices.

00:33:30.429 --> 00:33:35.820
Okay, now you can see that there are 3 clients
associated with the APs.

00:33:35.820 --> 00:33:40.760
To see a list of them, you can click clients,
here on the sidebar.

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:43.350
Here’s that list of clients.

00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:49.629
It shows their IP Addresses, which AP they
are associated with, which SSID they are using,

00:33:49.629 --> 00:33:50.629
etc.

00:33:50.629 --> 00:33:55.889
Okay, we’ve looked at a lot in this video,
but before we finish up let’s take a quick

00:33:55.889 --> 00:33:57.679
look at a couple more things.

00:33:57.679 --> 00:34:02.269
Let’s go to the wireless tab here.

00:34:02.269 --> 00:34:07.039
The first thing we’re shown is a list of
the APs that have joined with this WLC.

00:34:07.039 --> 00:34:11.530
You can see their IP addresses, model numbers,
MAC addresses, etc.

00:34:11.530 --> 00:34:16.169
Let’s click on an AP name and check the
settings.

00:34:16.169 --> 00:34:21.760
Again, here you can see a lot of information
about this specific AP.

00:34:21.760 --> 00:34:24.859
Look here, AP mode local.

00:34:24.859 --> 00:34:26.000
You should know what this is.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:29.740
Let’s check the other options.

00:34:29.740 --> 00:34:33.210
These are the operational modes I covered
in earlier videos.

00:34:33.210 --> 00:34:38.450
Local, flexconnect, monitor, rogue detector,
etc.

00:34:38.450 --> 00:34:42.859
This is where you can configure the AP’s
operational mode, but I’ll leave it at the

00:34:42.859 --> 00:34:44.570
default of local.

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:49.429
Okay, next let’s look at the management
tab.

00:34:49.429 --> 00:34:51.060
Here is the management tab.

00:34:51.060 --> 00:34:54.619
First, you can see a summary of the management
settings.

00:34:54.619 --> 00:35:01.250
For example, SNMPv1 is disabled, but v2 and
v3 are enabled.

00:35:01.250 --> 00:35:03.320
Syslog is currently disabled.

00:35:03.320 --> 00:35:07.250
HTTP and HTTPS connections are enabled.

00:35:07.250 --> 00:35:09.340
Telnet connections are disabled.

00:35:09.340 --> 00:35:15.910
To prove this I tried to Telnet from my PC
to the WLC, but the connection failed.

00:35:15.910 --> 00:35:19.720
Telnet is not a secure protocol, so it’s
best to leave it disabled.

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:25.559
SSH is enabled, and management via wireless
is disabled.

00:35:25.559 --> 00:35:30.780
This means that a wireless client won’t
be able to connect to the WLC and manage it.

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:33.460
Only a device connected to the wired network
can.

00:35:33.460 --> 00:35:40.720
Let’s change that setting by clicking on
management via wireless here.

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:44.960
You can change that setting by checking this
box here and then clicking apply.

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:51.079
If this is enabled, a wireless client, for
example a laptop using WiFi, will be able

00:35:51.079 --> 00:35:54.610
to connect to the WLC and make configuration
changes.

00:35:54.610 --> 00:35:59.589
Anyway, let’s look at one last thing, here
on the security tab.

00:35:59.589 --> 00:36:05.230
So, I clicked on the security tab and then
Access Control Lists here.

00:36:05.230 --> 00:36:11.070
Let’s configure an ACL to limit the management
traffic allowed to access the WLC.

00:36:11.070 --> 00:36:17.600
There are no ACLs at the moment, so I’ll
click here to make a new one.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:24.180
First I named the ACL MANAGEMENT_ACL, and
left the type as the default IPv4.

00:36:24.180 --> 00:36:26.760
Then I clicked apply to move forward.

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:33.420
Okay, now the ACL has been created, but as
you can see here it still has no rules.

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:41.359
So, I’ll click here to add a new rule and
specify what traffic can access the WLC.

00:36:41.359 --> 00:36:46.069
This is where you specify things like the
sequence number, source and destination IP,

00:36:46.069 --> 00:36:49.730
protocol, DSCP marking, direction, etc.

00:36:49.730 --> 00:36:55.551
So, I specified a sequence number, source
and destination, and then clicked on apply

00:36:55.551 --> 00:36:57.460
to make the rule.

00:36:57.460 --> 00:37:02.549
I followed that process again to make two
more rules, and now there are three rules

00:37:02.549 --> 00:37:03.980
in this ACL.

00:37:03.980 --> 00:37:09.049
Don’t worry about the exact contents of
these rules I’m making, I just want to show

00:37:09.049 --> 00:37:10.900
how to make an ACL.

00:37:10.900 --> 00:37:17.170
So, now that the ACL is made let’s apply
this ACL so that it limits access to manage

00:37:17.170 --> 00:37:18.650
the WLC.

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:25.070
To do so, click here, CPU access control lists.

00:37:25.070 --> 00:37:32.609
To apply the ACL, check enable CPU ACL here
and select the appropriate ACL from the list.

00:37:32.609 --> 00:37:34.990
then simply click on apply.

00:37:34.990 --> 00:37:36.540
And that’s all.

00:37:36.540 --> 00:37:42.730
So, CPU ACLs are used to limit access to the
CPU of the WLC.

00:37:42.730 --> 00:37:50.750
This limits which devices will be able to
connect to the WLC via Telnet/SSH, HTTP/HTTPS,

00:37:50.750 --> 00:37:53.710
retrieve SNMP information from the WLC, etc.

00:37:53.710 --> 00:38:00.069
This doesn’t affect traffic passing through
the WLC, only traffic destined directly for

00:38:00.069 --> 00:38:02.060
the WLC.

00:38:02.060 --> 00:38:08.119
Okay, there are so many more things I could
show you in the WLC, but this video is getting

00:38:08.119 --> 00:38:12.240
quite long and we’ve covered what we need
to for the CCNA.

00:38:12.240 --> 00:38:18.060
To practice for the CCNA you can just use
the WLC and APs in packet tracer, that’s

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:19.880
no problem at all.

00:38:19.880 --> 00:38:24.540
But if you’re interested in really exploring
what you can do with a WLC, you can probably

00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:29.870
get some second-hand hardware for cheap like
I did and set up your own home lab.

00:38:29.870 --> 00:38:34.440
But again, that’s not necessary for CCNA
studies.

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:40.560
Before moving on to the quiz, let’s review
what we learned in today’s video.

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:44.809
First I introduced the network topology we
used for today’s video.

00:38:44.809 --> 00:38:49.300
Then I showed the configurations I did on
the switch, such as IP addresses, interface

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:52.250
settings, and DHCP pools.

00:38:52.250 --> 00:38:57.750
Then I showed the basic WLC setup which is
required to access the GUI.

00:38:57.750 --> 00:39:01.540
Then I showed how to configure WLC interfaces.

00:39:01.540 --> 00:39:06.180
Remember the difference between physical ports
and logical interfaces.

00:39:06.180 --> 00:39:10.590
Up to now I’ve always used the terms port
and interface interchangeably, but when talking

00:39:10.590 --> 00:39:13.510
about WLCs you should be specific.

00:39:13.510 --> 00:39:18.470
I then showed how to configure WLANs on a
WLC.

00:39:18.470 --> 00:39:22.960
We configured the Internal WLAN and the Guest
WLAN.

00:39:22.960 --> 00:39:28.920
And finally we looked at some additional features,
such as how to configure a CPU ACL to limit

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:32.059
management traffic to the WLC.

00:39:32.059 --> 00:39:36.540
Make sure to watch until the end of the video
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:40.630
ExSim for CCNA, the best practice exams for
the CCNA.

00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:46.030
Okay, let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:39:46.030 --> 00:39:51.400
Which WLC port can be used to form an HA pair
with another WLC?

00:39:51.400 --> 00:39:55.579
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:39:55.579 --> 00:40:00.400
Okay, the answer is redundancy port.

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:03.960
The redundancy port in this image is number
9.

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:10.650
It can be used to connect the two WLCs together
to form a high availability, HA pair.

00:40:10.650 --> 00:40:15.630
One WLC will be active and the other will
be standby, ready to take over if the active

00:40:15.630 --> 00:40:16.630
one fails.

00:40:16.630 --> 00:40:21.030
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:40:21.030 --> 00:40:25.240
Which WLC interface type maps a WLAN to a
VLAN?

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:29.559
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:40:29.559 --> 00:40:35.569
Okay, the answer is A, dynamic interface.

00:40:35.569 --> 00:40:39.359
Dynamic interfaces are used to send traffic
between wireless clients and VLANs on the

00:40:39.359 --> 00:40:41.220
wired network.

00:40:41.220 --> 00:40:47.200
In this video, for example, we created two
dynamic interfaces, Internal and Guest, and

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:52.280
used them to map the Internal and Guest WLANs
to VLANs 100 and 200.

00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:57.410
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:40:57.410 --> 00:41:01.200
Which of the following is a type of Layer
3 authentication?

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:06.910
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:41:06.910 --> 00:41:10.250
The answer is D, web authentication.

00:41:10.250 --> 00:41:15.500
Web authentication can be configured under
the layer 3 security tab of a WLAN.

00:41:15.500 --> 00:41:20.460
It requires users to authenticate with a username
and password before being permitted to access

00:41:20.460 --> 00:41:21.480
the Internet.

00:41:21.480 --> 00:41:26.940
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:41:26.940 --> 00:41:31.130
Which WLC QoS setting should be used for video
traffic?

00:41:31.130 --> 00:41:34.819
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:41:34.819 --> 00:41:39.150
Okay, the answer is B, gold.

00:41:39.150 --> 00:41:41.410
Here are those QoS options again.

00:41:41.410 --> 00:41:46.440
Silver, best effort, is the default, but Gold
is recommended for video traffic.

00:41:46.440 --> 00:41:51.720
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:41:51.720 --> 00:41:56.730
Which WLC port type can form a LAG to pass
standard data traffic?

00:41:56.730 --> 00:42:00.490
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:42:00.490 --> 00:42:06.030
Okay, the answer is B, distribution system
port.

00:42:06.030 --> 00:42:10.590
These ports are the standard network ports
that the WLC uses to pass data traffic to

00:42:10.590 --> 00:42:12.550
and from wireless clients.

00:42:12.550 --> 00:42:14.770
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:42:14.770 --> 00:42:19.809
Now let’s take a look at a bonus question
from Boson Software’s ExSim for CCNA.

